<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1800,2005]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1800,1825]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small spiders with carapace relatively smooth. Some species with a bump-like projection in front of the spiracle opening in male (prespiracular bump). Genital organs typical for euophryines: embolus coiled anticlockwise (left palp, ventral view), tegulum with a proximal tegular lobe, retrolateral sperm duct loop present; epigynum with a window separated by the median septum. Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Gertsch" authorityName="Gertsch" box="[931,1126,1909,1933]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Neonella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[931,1032,1909,1933]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Neonella</emphasis>
Gertsch
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano" box="[1185,1337,1909,1933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" refString="Galiano, M. E. (1988) New species of Neonella Gertsch, 1936 (Araneae, Salticidae). Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 95, 439 - 448." type="journal article" year="1988">
Galiano 
<number box="[1280,1337,1909,1933]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) in body form, but differs in the absence of a lamella along the embolus and the prolateral sperm duct loop, and in the presence of the retrolateral sperm duct loop on the male palp.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,212]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,152,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Remarks.</emphasis>
Four species have been reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[752,867,151,175]" name="Venezuela" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[922,1017,151,175]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Platnick" box="[1032,1194,151,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" refString="Platnick, N. I. (2012) The world spider catalog, version 12.5. American Museum of Natural History, online at http: // research. amnh. org / iz / spiders / catalog." type="book" year="2012">
Platnick 
<number box="[1133,1194,151,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). A new species from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,244,188,212]" name="Ecuador" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
is described here.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
